******
[3] Macau
Date: Wed 22 Jun 2011
Source: The Macau Daily Times [edited]
http://www.macaudailytimes.com.mo/macau/26497-Macau-reports-cases-scarlet-fever-Hong-Kong-declares-outbreak.html


Hong Kong has declared an outbreak of scarlet fever, an illness
potentially fatal among children, after hundreds were infected in the
teeming city the government said yesterday [21 Jun 2011]. Macau's
Health Bureau (SSM) also confirmed a notable increase in the number of
cases and said it is closely monitoring the situation.

Authorities in the neighbouring special administrative region [Hong
Kong] closed a kindergarten for a week yesterday [21 Jun 2011] after
initial tests showed that a 2nd child may have died of scarlet fever.
The 5 year old boy, who died yesterday morning, went to a kindergarten
with 400 other children. While authorities have not detected any other
scarlet fever cases at the school, it was advised to close for a week.
"We will be monitoring the situation very closely," Thomas Tsang, a
medical doctor and controller of Hong Kong's Centre for Health
Protection (CHP), told a news conference.

Experts meanwhile warned that the epidemic sweeping through Hong
Kong, Macau, and parts of China may worsen. "The situation is rather
serious at the moment," Tsang added. "We are facing an epidemic
because the bacterium that is causing scarlet fever is widely
circulating in this region -- not only in Hong Kong but in mainland
China and Macau." In a statement released late yesterday [21 Jun
2011], the SSM said Macau has reported a notable increase in the
number of scarlet fever cases in recent months when compared to the
same period of last year [2010].

As of yesterday [21 Jun 2011], a total of 49 people were diagnosed
with scarlet fever this year [?in Macau], a surge from 29 and 16
cases, respectively, in 2009 and 2010. In May alone, the highest
number of 16 cases was reported. [Most of the infections were mild.]

The bureau [? Macau's Health Bureau or SSM] said 7 boys and 2 girls
were hospitalised for treatment, but no deaths have been reported so
far.

Children under 10 made up 93 per cent of the reported cases in Hong
Kong and most of the infections were mild. In Macau, among the 49
patients, 35 were boys and 14 were girls, and 53 per cent of them aged
between 5 and 8, and another 41 per cent between 2 and 4 years old.
Authorities urged parents and schools to keep a close eye on their
children and students and to report any suspicious cases.

Hong Kong authorities have recorded 40 new cases in the past few
days, pushing the total number to 459 so far this year [2011], the
highest annual total in the city and more than 3 times the figure for
the whole of 2010. "We have seen an unusually high number of cases
this year," the spokesman said, describing the situation as an
"outbreak". Scientists said the outbreak may be linked to a deadly new
strain of the disease, which could make it more contagious than in the
past. A unique gene fragment was present in the bacteria's genome
"which might contribute to increased transmissibility of this strain,"
said Hong Kong's CHP statement, released late Monday [20 Jun 2011].
The new strain, discovered by researchers at the University of Hong
Kong, appears to be resistant to antibiotics traditionally used to
fight the illness, the spokesman added.

